PowerShell (VS Code default)

Run these three lines in a new PowerShell terminal:

$env:Path = "C:\php81;" + $env:Path
$env:PHPRC = "C:\php81"             # tell PHP where php.ini lives
$env:PHP_INI_SCAN_DIR = ""          # stop scanning any other INI dirs


Verify:

where.exe php
php -v
php -m | findstr /i pdo_mysql


You should see C:\php81\php.exe, and pdo_mysql listed with no startup warnings.

Command Prompt (cmd.exe)

Run these in a new cmd window:

set "PATH=C:\php81;%PATH%"
set "PHPRC=C:\php81"
set "PHP_INI_SCAN_DIR="
where php
php -v
php -m | find /I "pdo_mysql"

Use the forced PHP for Laravel

Now run everything with this PHP:

php artisan config:clear
php artisan cache:clear
php artisan optimize:clear

php artisan serve --host=127.0.0.1 --port=8000

Try both login identifiers

Some panels use username instead of email.

Email: admin@gmail.com / Password: Admin@123!

Username: admin / Password: Admin@123!